This paper focuses on designing a deep learning structure for predicting mental disorders from speech samples. The use of pre-trained models for text and audio encoding, as well as the incorporation of emotion-specific embeddings and transfer learning, suggests a strong emphasis on natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) techniques. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper deals with clinical interviews and mental health, which suggests a potential fit for sub-categories such as cs.SD (Sound), cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the use of deep learning models and multimodal fusion techniques suggests a potential fit for cs.LG (Machine Learning).
